The earliest voltammetric measurement was normal polarography at a DME (Bard and Faulkner, 2001; Harvey, 2000). This classic technique was invented by Heyrovsky, Noble prize laureate of chemistry 1959 (Butler and Zuman, 1967). In normal polarography the linear scan of the potential produce voltammograms (Fig. 6.27
                           ) (Harvey, 2000). Polarography is done in an unstirred solution; however, falling Hg drops cause a limiting current. The growth of the Hg drop, which causes the current oscillations, may also lead to a time-dependent change in the area of the WE (Harvey, 2000). Due to the special properties of this electrode (e.g., renewable surface and wide cathodic potential range), polarography has been used extensively for the determination of many important reducible species (Wang, 2006). Normal polarography has been replaced by different types of pulse polarography (Fig. 6.28
                           ), e.g., differential pulse polarography, normal pulse polarography, staircase polarography, and square-wave polarography. Here, limiting and peak currents are in linear relationship with analyte concentration. Moreover, half-wave and peak potentials can be used for qualitative analysis. The sensitivity and detection limits of pulse polarography is higher than those in normal polarography (Harvey, 2000). Polarography is used extensively for the analysis of metal ions, inorganic anions (e.g., IO3
                           − and NO3
                           −) and organic compounds, which can be easily reduced or oxidized (carbonyls, carboxylic acids, and carbon–carbon double bonds) (Harvey, 2000).

Electrochemical methods can be used in detection of a wide range of pharmaceutical and biological compounds with great sensitivity, portability, cost-effective price, and no extensive pretreatment. In addition, due to the excellent features of CNMs, such as low cost, chemical stability, high surface area, high conductivity, and good electrocatalytical activity, they’ve gained much interest in all areas of electrochemistry with various applications from energy conversion and storage to electroanalysis. Here, we will review the latest synthesis, characterization, and application of carbonaceous nanomaterials in the case of pharmaceutical electroanalysis (Table 6.1
                  ). However, because of the large activity and high number of 

                  reports in this field, we apologize to the authors of excellent work unintentionally not mentioned here.
